         <abstract>
            <p>Too much money is being borrowed, especially from commercial banks. Not enough is being taken in taxes and loans from individuals. The increase in bank credit has propensities for inflation, and also creates problems in debt management and postwar maintenance of security prices and bank reserves. The inflationary threat in the redemption feature of War Savings Bonds, plus the inadequacy of subscriptions to these bonds, argues for heavier taxation, and failing that for compulsory savings, or bond redemption at the option of the government. The short-term borrowing program has been wise, and well managed.</p>
         </abstract>
